{\rlap{--} I_{ij}} = \int {\rho \left( {{x_i}{x_j} - \frac{1}{3}{\delta _{ij}}{r^2}} \right){d^3}r,}
$$\end{document}
where i, j=1, 2, 3 are spatial indices and \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$r = \sqrt {{x^2} + {y^2} + {z^2}}$$\end{document} is the distance to the source. The two polarizations of the gravitational wave field, h+ and h×, can be computed in terms of \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
